1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:29,379
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa

2
00:00:29,579 --> 00:00:38,808
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:38,990 --> 00:00:52,465
The first thing was to just make sure that everybody understands that after this talk, really, the rest of the day until five o'clock is for you, really.

4
00:00:59,954 --> 00:01:14,272
And it's meant to be just a time for doing some reflection about your life and whatnot, about the past year, trying to make some of these resolutions for the next year, which we never keep.

5
00:01:15,775 --> 00:01:19,278
But they're there, you know, it's part of our good intentions.

6
00:01:20,620 --> 00:01:23,564
And I just wanted to...

7
00:01:26,025 --> 00:01:37,469
really say a few things and then perhaps just to contemplate the life of Saddam Hussein as a sort of point of reflection.

8
00:01:39,593 --> 00:01:53,811
The first thing was to talk about, they're actually sort of monastic vows coming, I suppose, more clearly from the Christian tradition, but I think it might be better to just call them spiritual undertakings or communal undertakings.

9
00:01:55,194 --> 00:01:57,197
I've called them S to the power of four.

10
00:01:59,439 --> 00:02:05,668
The first one is sufficiency, sometimes simplicity, what in the old days they used to call poverty.

11
00:02:07,588 --> 00:02:09,592
The second one is surrender.

12
00:02:10,492 --> 00:02:13,657
What in the old days they used to call obedience, but nobody likes that word these days.

13
00:02:14,998 --> 00:02:16,120
It's too hard for the ego.

14
00:02:16,980 --> 00:02:19,465
Don't want to be obedient.

15
00:02:19,485 --> 00:02:21,127
The third one is celibacy.

16
00:02:21,728 --> 00:02:22,187
Say no more.

17
00:02:23,430 --> 00:02:25,492
And the fourth one is service.

18
00:02:26,653 --> 00:02:31,259
So these are four sort of things that we can contemplate about our lives.

19
00:02:32,161 --> 00:02:34,844
So the first one, this sufficiency thing,

20
00:02:34,960 --> 00:02:35,800
That's a nice word.

21
00:02:36,162 --> 00:02:37,104
What is sufficient?

22
00:02:37,383 --> 00:02:44,056
You know, it brings us into this ecological business and the way the world is at this present time.

23
00:02:45,157 --> 00:02:46,038
What is sufficient?

24
00:02:46,900 --> 00:02:53,711
You just go through your wardrobe and ask yourself, well, what's actually sufficient?

25
00:02:55,901 --> 00:03:06,697
That doesn't mean to say you have to be rigorous to the point of self-denial or sort of self-mortification so you end up with one pair of shoes or something.

26
00:03:07,919 --> 00:03:12,085
It's more the sense of recognizing that certain times of our lives we need different shoes.

27
00:03:12,264 --> 00:03:18,854
So even I, you see, I have a pair of pumps, proper walking shoes.

28
00:03:21,018 --> 00:03:22,319
I've got a pair of ordinary shoes.

29
00:03:22,479 --> 00:03:23,360
I've got slippers, you see.

30
00:03:25,146 --> 00:03:29,393
Now I would say that's sufficient for me.

31
00:03:32,356 --> 00:03:39,806
So it's not a case of having some sort of absolute standard, but just to look at what one has.

32
00:03:40,567 --> 00:03:47,757
Go around the house and just go around your flat, your house, and just keep asking yourself, is this sufficient?

33
00:03:47,836 --> 00:03:48,538
Is this enough?

34
00:03:49,581 --> 00:03:59,776
I remember when I sold my house just before I joined the order, I had four garden forks.

35
00:03:59,795 --> 00:04:03,540
I don't know how I ended up with four garden forks.

36
00:04:03,561 --> 00:04:10,949
But I must have just gone into a shop and thought, that's a nice garden fork, and bought it, and come back and I've got this stock of garden forks.

37
00:04:12,331 --> 00:04:15,977
I had lots of knives, massive amount of plates, don't know where they came from.

38
00:04:17,644 --> 00:04:19,867
Well, of course, I heave them all off onto poor friends.

39
00:04:20,247 --> 00:04:21,129
I don't know what they've done with them.

40
00:04:22,550 --> 00:04:25,894
So this idea of simplicity, sufficiency.

41
00:04:27,055 --> 00:04:36,906
If you look at the monastic order, going back to the Buddha's time himself, of course, you've got, you know, taking into consideration the climate.

42
00:04:39,848 --> 00:04:45,475
Housing was, you know, under a tree during the dry season, in a hut during the wet season.

43
00:04:48,120 --> 00:05:17,384
and you built it just out of local grass and whatnot so that's how simple you can get in this climate I suppose you need a shed with some cladding so when you look at your house you know most of us have sort of nice houses, nice flats and when you realize that you've got more than sufficiency then

44
00:05:18,461 --> 00:05:19,882
you know, we should relax into that.

45
00:05:20,084 --> 00:05:24,048
We should say, oh yeah, you know, I'm lucky, I've got more than I actually need.

46
00:05:25,509 --> 00:05:27,350
If you feel guilty about it, we'll sell your house.

47
00:05:28,211 --> 00:05:30,173
But I'm not, I don't think you should.

48
00:05:30,934 --> 00:05:40,824
What I'm saying is that sometimes we get into this consumerism where we're always going for the next thing, for the next big house, the next fashion.

49
00:05:41,485 --> 00:05:44,588
But actually, if you keep asking yourself what's sufficient,

50
00:05:45,935 --> 00:05:48,997
then contentment arises easily.

51
00:05:49,237 --> 00:05:50,399
You're just content with that.

52
00:05:50,519 --> 00:05:54,363
And then you're thankful that you've got more than you feel is sufficient.

53
00:05:58,247 --> 00:06:03,052
So it's just a nice little reflection on the simplicity of life, sufficiency.

54
00:06:06,776 --> 00:06:14,524
In the early days, the monks and nuns were happy with just rag robes taken off corpses, you know, left on the charnel grounds.

55
00:06:15,297 --> 00:06:20,244
That's what they did, just the animals would come and eat the corpses, or they'd just corrupt.

56
00:06:22,706 --> 00:06:23,728
And they sewed them together.

57
00:06:24,528 --> 00:06:25,790
But the Buddha wasn't happy with that.

58
00:06:27,452 --> 00:06:37,266
He didn't like when he saw groups of monks just in rag roads, just tied higgledy-piggledy, washed but obviously dirtied.

59
00:06:37,326 --> 00:06:38,487
He didn't like that at all, did he?

60
00:06:38,869 --> 00:06:45,016
So he ended up by asking them to sew them in a way that reminded them of paddy fields.

61
00:06:45,959 --> 00:07:07,612
so these robes are like paddy field I've got strips and then he said to dye them with this particular nut give them a sort of browny colour so there was a sense of sense of beauty or orderliness about it yeah

62
00:07:11,288 --> 00:07:20,000
And it's for us to decide individually where that line is for us.

63
00:07:20,019 --> 00:07:21,201
It's an interesting question, isn't it?

64
00:07:21,483 --> 00:07:24,927
Because he himself probably would have lived like that for quite a long time.

65
00:07:24,987 --> 00:07:36,603
And then suddenly there's this idea of getting everybody to dress the same and having some sort of uniformed

66
00:07:41,427 --> 00:07:50,521
In Plato's understanding, if I get it right, please correct me otherwise, these three come together, you see, wisdom, goodness and beauty.

67
00:07:53,985 --> 00:07:54,487
Beauty.

68
00:07:57,050 --> 00:08:07,286
It's interesting that in the Abhidhamma, all those mental states that are unwholesome, they actually call unskillful, but the ones that are wholesome, they use the word beautiful, sober.

69
00:08:10,290 --> 00:08:10,370
See?

70
00:08:11,684 --> 00:08:26,586
So you have to be careful not to grow yourself into a sort of rigorous prune-like existence, dried prune existence.

71
00:08:27,726 --> 00:08:33,296
There has to be a certain levity about the spiritual life.

72
00:08:33,316 --> 00:08:35,599
There has to be a certain seasoning to it.

73
00:08:40,067 --> 00:08:48,457
So, we can look at that, the idea of sufficiency in our lives, the idea of simplicity, and just check it out, you see.

74
00:08:48,477 --> 00:08:51,922
You go back, see what you've got, etc.

75
00:08:52,903 --> 00:08:55,025
It's not only with what you have, but how you live.

76
00:08:58,850 --> 00:09:10,024
So, spiritually speaking, we have this core, we have this aim, you might say, this objective, which we call nibbana, you see.

77
00:09:11,388 --> 00:09:40,736
now whether we have an idea of Nibbana or what it is the fact is that it's a matter of purifying the heart the purification of the heart that has to go on so you look at your activities and ask yourself why am I doing that to the simplest of things like why am I watching this program remembering that anything I attend to is an act of intention and therefore it's conditioning me so if I attend to a program which is

78
00:09:41,206 --> 00:09:44,269
just silly, just nothing, you know.

79
00:09:44,490 --> 00:09:47,474
It comes under wrong speech in the sense of sampalapala.

80
00:09:47,754 --> 00:09:49,014
How do you translate that?

81
00:09:50,076 --> 00:09:52,840
A gossip, useless speech, useless speech.

82
00:09:53,780 --> 00:09:56,183
So you're watching a program which is basically useless.

83
00:09:58,486 --> 00:10:00,509
And that's time, you see, time.

84
00:10:03,373 --> 00:10:08,479
We talk about this word, samvega, which means a sort of sense of urgency about the spiritual life.

85
00:10:09,606 --> 00:10:22,519
When we consider the brevity of our life, sickness, old age and death, and to pull ourselves up short and ask ourselves, why am I watching that program?

86
00:10:28,118 --> 00:10:29,480
Why am I going to that show?

87
00:10:29,880 --> 00:10:31,123
Why am I going to that film?

88
00:10:31,143 --> 00:10:33,086
Why am I with these friends?

89
00:10:33,446 --> 00:10:35,789
See, they might not be the right friends anymore.

90
00:10:36,211 --> 00:10:41,359
A lot of people who begin to move spiritually find they leave old friendships.

91
00:10:41,399 --> 00:10:46,206
It's not that they blame them or criticize them or anything like that.

92
00:10:46,307 --> 00:10:51,595
It's just that they don't draw them anymore and there's a shift over to another type of friend.

93
00:10:54,038 --> 00:10:55,279
That can be a conscious thing.

94
00:10:55,461 --> 00:10:57,644
Often it's quite unconscious in the spiritual life.

95
00:10:57,664 --> 00:11:02,452
You do things not fully aware that in fact you're moving.

96
00:11:02,874 --> 00:11:08,364
And then you realize your friends aren't calling you up.

97
00:11:08,384 --> 00:11:12,672
Because they got fed up with you and all your Buddhist stuff.

98
00:11:15,587 --> 00:11:24,263
So there's that simplicity, that sufficiency, drives its flavor into all areas of our lives.

99
00:11:25,465 --> 00:11:28,149
All you have to keep saying is, is this sufficient?

100
00:11:28,490 --> 00:11:31,515
Is this simplicity?

101
00:11:33,239 --> 00:11:36,163
And it just clarifies life.

102
00:11:36,224 --> 00:11:37,426
It makes life very simple.

103
00:11:37,466 --> 00:11:40,751
Life itself takes a lot of stress away.

104
00:11:42,014 --> 00:11:49,302
Because if you're doing things which are against the flow, against the flow of your spiritual life, you see, it's always drawing energy away.

105
00:11:51,424 --> 00:11:52,926
Unnecessary energy loss.

106
00:11:57,552 --> 00:12:01,897
The second one is surrender, which in the old days was called obedience.

107
00:12:04,239 --> 00:12:06,721
So surrender in the spiritual life is...

108
00:12:07,241 --> 00:12:13,067
abandoning one's own ideas and lending oneself to the teachings.

109
00:12:15,691 --> 00:12:28,624
So that's, every time you feel that resistance to what the spiritual life is calling you to, you see, you see it as something which is negative, drawing you away.

110
00:12:28,683 --> 00:12:33,469
So you have to make that act of surrender, yield,

111
00:12:37,162 --> 00:12:38,604
I think they have that in the States, don't they?

112
00:12:38,624 --> 00:12:42,467
When you go to a crossroad, yield.

113
00:12:42,488 --> 00:12:45,192
I think it is.

114
00:12:45,211 --> 00:12:45,751
Yield.

115
00:12:46,092 --> 00:12:46,793
What a lovely word.

116
00:12:48,696 --> 00:12:49,197
See?

117
00:12:49,216 --> 00:12:52,801
So you have to surrender to what the spiritual life is asking you to do.

118
00:12:57,527 --> 00:13:01,951
So we've got these basic rules, these basic, you know, not to kill people like that.

119
00:13:02,513 --> 00:13:04,434
But...

120
00:13:05,748 --> 00:13:07,370
they always have their opposites.

121
00:13:07,730 --> 00:13:16,043
So when the first rule is not to harm any living being that moves quickly towards to take care of all living beings.

122
00:13:18,187 --> 00:13:25,018
Not to take what is not freely given moves very easily into to give what is not being asked for.

123
00:13:28,283 --> 00:13:29,245
That's not quite right, is it?

124
00:13:29,765 --> 00:13:31,788
To give even though

125
00:13:32,984 --> 00:14:02,923
to give when asked but to give when you're not asked you know where you see a need yeah so if you take all all those negative side the way that you don't do things you see you've only got to see that actually not doing those things because we're in time because we're in time and space and events have to happen they're always beckoning you to do the opposite okay

126
00:14:07,038 --> 00:14:18,970
So at all times, you see, Sunday morning, you know, when there's that, you know, you wake up and there's that desire just to turn over, roast the other side.

127
00:14:20,871 --> 00:14:24,355
You see, and then the call comes, get up and meditate.

128
00:14:27,379 --> 00:14:29,740
Resistance.

129
00:14:29,760 --> 00:14:33,804
And then just to do as the old sailors did on the hammocks, you see, show a leg.

130
00:14:34,054 --> 00:14:42,929
You shake it out and get a feel of the air out there and then sort of shake it off and say to yourself, God, I've got to surrender to the path, you see.

131
00:14:42,950 --> 00:14:44,756
I've got to be obedient to it.

132
00:14:55,822 --> 00:15:19,535
where we find ourselves in situations that demand that we follow a certain rule even coming here just following the rotor going into a workplace with their rules and regulations going to see a friend and washing the pots like they wash the pots can be enormously annoying can't it when somebody comes in and washes the pots in a different way than you wash

133
00:15:19,955 --> 00:15:28,785
And it's just using those little situations where you're going against your own conditioning just to loosen you up a bit.

134
00:15:30,729 --> 00:15:38,839
That's one of the benefits of coming on a retreat, especially a strong retreat, because it snaps some of the old habits.

135
00:15:39,239 --> 00:15:40,961
And then you know, it gives you strength.

136
00:15:41,001 --> 00:15:43,264
You know that you don't have to behave like that.

137
00:15:45,246 --> 00:15:47,649
Even not eating, you see, after lunch.

138
00:15:48,827 --> 00:15:51,613
Then you realize, oh yeah, nothing happens when I don't eat after lunch.

139
00:15:52,855 --> 00:15:53,515
Nothing happens.

140
00:15:56,681 --> 00:16:00,206
And then to take a day's fast and realize that nothing happens either.

141
00:16:03,631 --> 00:16:09,241
And that allows us just to be more easy with life, be able to move and shift with things, you know.

142
00:16:10,182 --> 00:16:12,506
Not to get upset, you get on a train and it's late.

143
00:16:13,144 --> 00:16:14,105
That's the way it is, you know.

144
00:16:14,125 --> 00:16:16,409
People get very upset about that.

145
00:16:16,429 --> 00:16:18,032
Well, I must say, the British aren't so bad.

146
00:16:20,416 --> 00:16:22,197
Usually a joke runs around the place.

147
00:16:23,059 --> 00:16:29,249
You're used to it, especially when, you know, they very truthfully announced to you that the train's been delayed because there's a cow on the line.

148
00:16:31,692 --> 00:16:36,779
A great sort of announcements are made, you know.

149
00:16:36,799 --> 00:16:38,221
Leaves on the line, things like that.

150
00:16:38,523 --> 00:16:40,164
I must say, it's all got much better now.

151
00:16:42,946 --> 00:16:44,807
But you're driving along and you're in a traffic jam.

152
00:16:47,291 --> 00:16:47,912
What are you going to do?

153
00:16:50,914 --> 00:16:53,357
So that's when you surrender to the situation.

154
00:16:53,398 --> 00:16:56,501
The situation is asking you to let go of what you want.

155
00:16:57,023 --> 00:17:00,285
And to see the situation as it is.

156
00:17:00,386 --> 00:17:07,335
And of course with that surrendering to the situation, yielding to the way it is, all that stress just evaporates.

157
00:17:07,355 --> 00:17:07,775
This is it.

158
00:17:07,795 --> 00:17:09,257
This is the way it is.

159
00:17:10,469 --> 00:17:20,442
So that sense of surrender, of yielding, you see, once we're in the habit of that, life just becomes a little easier for us.

160
00:17:24,626 --> 00:17:26,429
Even our own self-expectations.

161
00:17:26,750 --> 00:17:30,595
I remember somebody came to visit me in London and they got lost.

162
00:17:31,915 --> 00:17:35,641
Normally we'd only take them so much, but for some reason they took a turn off before they knew it.

163
00:17:36,662 --> 00:17:39,665
You know, a one-hour journey took something like two or three hours.

164
00:17:41,164 --> 00:17:43,907
And when they came, they said to me, it was amazing.

165
00:17:44,088 --> 00:17:46,892
In the old days, they'd have got really ratty with themselves.

166
00:17:46,912 --> 00:17:51,417
You know, they'd have punched themselves in the nose and butted a wall or something.

167
00:17:51,438 --> 00:17:55,102
But this time, they just took it as a different way to come and visit me.

168
00:17:56,763 --> 00:17:57,285
And it's that.

169
00:17:57,765 --> 00:18:05,755
You see, that sense of surrendering also to ourselves, just giving up on our own dictates, little dictates that we give to ourselves.

170
00:18:09,328 --> 00:18:15,720
So there's that whole area of looking at your life from the point of view of surrendering, yielding to situations.

171
00:18:18,423 --> 00:18:22,852
Of course we draw a line, we draw a line at the point of unskillfulness, at the point where we're doing harm.

172
00:18:23,452 --> 00:18:33,750
Sometimes that's not such an easy line to see, but as long as we don't mean to do harm, remember there's that

173
00:18:33,730 --> 00:18:53,950
And there's that stress in the Buddha's teaching that to do harm which is going to lead away from the awakening, away from off the path, is that harm that we intend, not that harm that we end up doing without us knowing.

174
00:18:57,962 --> 00:19:14,526
In fact, the story that goes with the Dhammapada verse that I read out last night, the opening about everything is mine made, is a story about, you know, and if you do evil, it follows you like the wheel of a cart and all that, the hoof of an ox.

175
00:19:15,386 --> 00:19:23,498
And the story with that is of this Arahant who's doing walking meditation, and he's crunching all these ants, so there's blood all over the place.

176
00:19:25,250 --> 00:19:27,413
And the monks say to the Buddha, well, look what he's done.

177
00:19:27,432 --> 00:19:30,395
He's done this terrible harm that he's done to all these ants, you see.

178
00:19:31,397 --> 00:19:32,378
The Buddha says, well, he's blind.

179
00:19:32,499 --> 00:19:33,299
He doesn't know what he's doing.

180
00:19:33,861 --> 00:19:35,623
He doesn't see where he's going, you see.

181
00:19:36,144 --> 00:19:41,390
And then there's always these little add-ons, these bolt-ons that they put about in the past life.

182
00:19:42,652 --> 00:19:45,434
He killed so many ants or something that it's all coming back to him.

183
00:19:46,141 --> 00:19:59,188
But that aside, it's a case of recognizing that when we come across those shady areas where we don't quite know if it's right or wrong because of circumstance.

184
00:20:00,586 --> 00:20:09,818
not to be afraid to make decisions which you're not clear about, but intend at least to do what's for the benefit of others, benefit of oneself.

185
00:20:10,440 --> 00:20:17,450
And that's something the Buddha always says, see, for the benefit of oneself, for the benefit of the other, both for the benefit of oneself and the other.

186
00:20:18,411 --> 00:20:20,775
So there are times that you do things for your own benefit.

187
00:20:21,174 --> 00:20:23,178
That's not being selfish, that's self-caring.

188
00:20:23,898 --> 00:20:26,542
That's another area where we sometimes become confused.

189
00:20:32,750 --> 00:20:38,621
The third one, celibacy, I always like to coin a phrase from Churchill.

190
00:20:39,422 --> 00:20:44,651
Some are born celibate, some become celibate, and others have celibacy thrust upon them.

191
00:20:47,115 --> 00:20:54,088
So there's always times in our lives where we find that we're not in a relationship.

192
00:20:55,290 --> 00:20:57,153
So those are times to...

193
00:20:58,196 --> 00:21:04,808
So we see what the role of sexuality and romance and friendship and certain types of friendships play in our lives.

194
00:21:05,851 --> 00:21:09,297
And to recognize that that's an option.

195
00:21:09,698 --> 00:21:10,779
It's not a necessity.

196
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:17,511
Ever since Freud, sex has taken the sort of need role of food.

197
00:21:18,032 --> 00:21:19,095
But I mean, you know, it's not.

198
00:21:20,037 --> 00:21:21,318
You can live without it.

199
00:21:21,755 --> 00:21:36,010
So that when we find ourselves in situations where there isn't that sort of relationship about, well, that's the time to really just open up to that situation and relax into it.

200
00:21:36,030 --> 00:21:42,038
If one wants to go there, then one makes the intention to move that way.

201
00:21:42,499 --> 00:21:46,242
But if it becomes an obsession, then it creates a lot of suffering, doesn't it?

202
00:21:54,019 --> 00:22:06,472
Now the question is, why is celibacy seen as always part of a direct path in terms of the spiritual life, especially in Buddhism?

203
00:22:07,094 --> 00:22:11,659
Was it because the Buddha himself was celibate and he was just bitter about it?

204
00:22:12,118 --> 00:22:15,702
He didn't want anybody else to have a good time.

205
00:22:16,703 --> 00:22:19,487
Hell, I'm going to not do it, nobody else is going to do it.

206
00:22:19,467 --> 00:22:25,294
And it's because, of course, of the attachment.

207
00:22:26,694 --> 00:22:30,720
It's always this business of seeking happiness in the wrong place.

208
00:22:33,182 --> 00:22:48,681
So we can see that seeking happiness in just the physicality of a relationship, just the sexual act of a thing, just by itself, is empty, it doesn't go anywhere.

209
00:22:50,669 --> 00:23:14,482
usually quote Woody Allen now when he says sex is an empty just sex is an empty experience but as empty experiences go so that that aside and with romance is a very strong sort of connection with a person

210
00:23:16,588 --> 00:23:41,009
which comes and goes of course leading to a deeper friendship there's that mistake of one's own happiness dependent on that person that's where the suffering is because you know when that person leaves or dies there's this huge hole in one's heart grief and all that so

211
00:23:41,480 --> 00:23:56,998
you know, to see it as a time, if you find yourself not in a relationship and you want a relationship, to see that actual desire for relationship as actually seeking happiness, you see, seeking happiness there.

212
00:23:57,018 --> 00:24:02,983
So the question mark is, how can you have that sort of relationship without that sort of dependency?

213
00:24:05,027 --> 00:24:06,188
So that's the conundrum.

214
00:24:15,330 --> 00:24:33,069
the fact that the Buddha, having attained enlightenment, did not go back to the married life, is a bit of a downer, because it then might have suggested that having attained that enlightenment, there was still that sort of re-engagement in life.

215
00:24:35,310 --> 00:24:43,085
But there's a suggestion there that in the Buddha's life and within the tradition that that's not possible.

216
00:24:43,746 --> 00:24:48,233
Now in later Buddhism, of course, there was a movement against that, wasn't there?

217
00:24:48,253 --> 00:24:57,289
To the lay life as being the way that one could also attain full liberation.

218
00:24:57,309 --> 00:24:58,652
And I think that...

219
00:24:59,948 --> 00:25:05,436
you know, in the lay life, one has to look at that and see the possibility.

220
00:25:05,877 --> 00:25:13,230
I don't see it as something which necessarily has to be against the spiritual life at all.

221
00:25:15,153 --> 00:25:25,450
I much prefer the Hindus on this one, you know, their way of approaching the whole spiritual life through a total engagement in

222
00:25:26,492 --> 00:25:28,656
in communal life.

223
00:25:28,957 --> 00:25:38,393
So, you know, the Brahminical way, I mean, it is a bit patriarchal about the man, but equally so for the woman.

224
00:25:39,255 --> 00:25:43,261
The first 25 years, a student, around that.

225
00:25:43,281 --> 00:25:48,130
Then you're supposed to marry, and you have children, etc., and you go through all that.

226
00:25:48,733 --> 00:26:04,557
And then round about 60 or so, when all the children have grown up and all that's done, you remove yourself from society with your wife and try to live more separately, sort of letting go of life, a renunciation, post-renunciation.

227
00:26:04,577 --> 00:26:07,903
And then when you're 75, you kick your wife out.

228
00:26:09,967 --> 00:26:11,568
It happens to your wife.

229
00:26:13,337 --> 00:26:16,663
But presumably she's kicked the bloke out as well.

230
00:26:17,182 --> 00:26:24,073
But the point is that separation at the end of life, meeting, you know, trying to go beyond that attachment to the world.

231
00:26:26,056 --> 00:26:33,566
So that, I think, is a very fruitful image to have in one's mind about the process of renunciation in the lay life.

232
00:26:33,885 --> 00:26:36,789
And, of course, you know, devoting yourself.

233
00:26:36,829 --> 00:26:40,154
Well, the next bit, the next I'll talk about is, of course, service.

234
00:26:40,792 --> 00:26:50,269
So that's where this slips into, you know, all these things come out in that outward flow, see?

235
00:26:51,452 --> 00:26:56,761
The sufficiency, the surrender, the celibacy is something which is internal.

236
00:26:56,781 --> 00:26:58,425
Of course, it affects our relationships.

237
00:26:58,945 --> 00:27:03,595
But then somehow there has to be an outward flowing of that, and that's the sense of service.

238
00:27:09,311 --> 00:27:12,915
So it's just one of these paradoxes that we're most happy when we're giving.

239
00:27:14,376 --> 00:27:25,127
As soon as that giving becomes self-conscious and we're doing it in order to feel happy, in order to feel worthy for fame and all that sort of stuff, then it becomes cancer.

240
00:27:25,188 --> 00:27:28,511
Then demands are put on that service.

241
00:27:28,751 --> 00:27:30,993
We only do certain things that make us happy.

242
00:27:31,755 --> 00:27:33,497
And you end up being a do-gooder, don't you?

243
00:27:36,008 --> 00:27:45,003
A working definition of a do-gooder is the person who does you the good they want to do you, whether you want it or not.

244
00:27:45,786 --> 00:27:58,167
The usual example I give is if you know somebody's sick and you go along with your chicken soup,

245
00:27:58,672 --> 00:28:01,615
And they say, well, I'm just too sick.

246
00:28:01,635 --> 00:28:03,057
I can't have that.

247
00:28:03,077 --> 00:28:04,298
I'm terribly sorry.

248
00:28:04,318 --> 00:28:05,480
Well, of course, you understand that.

249
00:28:05,840 --> 00:28:08,183
You're a bit disappointed, but you understand that.

250
00:28:08,203 --> 00:28:10,227
And they say, but listen, you could do something for me.

251
00:28:10,247 --> 00:28:11,087
You say, sure, what's that?

252
00:28:11,528 --> 00:28:12,529
Could you clean my toilet?

253
00:28:16,855 --> 00:28:19,519
You had all these highfalutin ideas about how to help somebody.

254
00:28:19,538 --> 00:28:20,799
All you do is clean the toilet.

255
00:28:22,261 --> 00:28:26,788
So that sense of service is...

256
00:28:29,182 --> 00:28:35,354
giving up one's own desires for the benefit of others, looking at the world from the other's point of view.

257
00:28:35,433 --> 00:28:41,204
Now, there's a scripture in which the Buddha visits these three Arahants.

258
00:28:41,224 --> 00:28:47,696
Now, fair enough, they're fully enlightened and haven't got any selfishness left, and they're living together perfectly peacefully.

259
00:28:47,778 --> 00:28:50,962
and the Buddha's with them, and he asks them, he says, how do you do it?

260
00:28:51,002 --> 00:28:52,424
How do you live peacefully like this?

261
00:28:54,308 --> 00:28:59,277
And, of course, living out in the forest, in your hut, I mean, it's very simple.

262
00:29:00,458 --> 00:29:11,997
But Anuruddha says, well, you know, we get up in the morning, go on Pindapad, we go on our arms round, and whoever's last out prepares the stuff for people coming back.

263
00:29:12,567 --> 00:29:39,417
and then we all come back with our food and we share it out and whoever's last eating clears up that's it there's no there's no once once if you if you consider once the other once your attention is on the other what the other wants life becomes very easy isn't it because always because people are always looking out for you and you're always looking out for them

264
00:29:39,719 --> 00:29:46,609
So it becomes a sort of society based on this idea of generosity, on dana, you see.

265
00:29:48,212 --> 00:29:59,330
As soon as you're playing your part and you're putting the other first, and then you see the other ones actually putting themselves first, then you get that shaking, don't you?

266
00:30:00,609 --> 00:30:05,515
So it needs a sort of communal effort for everybody to live on behalf of the other.

267
00:30:06,096 --> 00:30:10,701
And because everybody's looking out for the other, you see, then you have this harmony.

268
00:30:13,344 --> 00:30:14,846
At least that's the theory.

269
00:30:18,789 --> 00:30:22,534
But as soon as somebody holds a position, you've had it, you see.

270
00:30:23,674 --> 00:30:28,760
In the Buddhist order, there are these rules of how to work with disputes.

271
00:30:29,517 --> 00:30:40,790
So there are those disputes that have to be put under the mat and just leave it alone because you just get so caught up in what's right, what's wrong.

272
00:30:44,474 --> 00:30:55,288
But keeping that in mind, I suppose the danger of putting the other first, especially with others who aren't doing that, is that they can abuse you.

273
00:30:58,204 --> 00:31:05,121
But generosity doesn't demand that you find yourself being abused, being used.

274
00:31:06,884 --> 00:31:09,852
You yourself have to be sensitive to that.

275
00:31:13,814 --> 00:31:22,442
So these are sort of four ways that you can look back on the years, you would say, on what you have and what you do with your life.

276
00:31:23,424 --> 00:31:40,242
The idea of sufficiency, the idea of surrendering to the path, doing what the path asks, that whole area of relationship, what sort of relationships do you want to cultivate, and the idea of service.

277
00:31:41,724 --> 00:31:43,855
It's just four points of recollection.

